social_posts.post_text: 36 hour whirlwind of hardcore luxuriating, flamingoes (my god to be born hot pink and that gorgeous), and soul-warming sunshine 💜💜💜

People asked me why I got a doula when I was pregnant—some of them thought it was a trendy wellnessy indulgence. Black women die at 3 times the rate of white women from pregnancy related causes in America because of racial bias. Misconceptions like Black women have a higher pain threshold—hard to not choke on that one, it sounds like a sentiment from the days of slavery, but it’s still pervasive—play a role, as well as the fact that we’re not listened to by medical professionals when something is wrong and much of the time we have access to substandard medical care. 

I’m scared to die in a hospital because the person looking after me thinks I don’t feel pain like a human being. I’m also limp with rage that my skin color makes me more likely to die in even this scenario. It’s enough to make you never want to leave your bed.
 
Studies show (and other countries that don’t have our staggering maternal death rate have shown for years and years) that access to doulas is one of the most effective interventions in helping to close the maternal death rate gap. Read this article in the NY Times from this week—it’s about a doula program in St. Louis that’s saving Black women’s lives.
 
Also tagging @oulahealth here bc they’re doing a beautiful job of making doulas and midwifery more accessible (Oula is a new birthing clinic w locations in Manhattan and Brooklyn that brilliantly combines obstetrics and midwifery AND takes insurance). During the unhurried visits they talk in depth about things like nutrition, mental wellbeing, exercise….and the offices are chic and cozy and unmedical feeling)

We are mesmerized! Big, beautiful, charged, colorful portraits of Black people living their lives, looking majestic, looking ordinary and tired, triumphing, succumbing to madness, soaring, suffering—by LA-based artist Henry Taylor. (How did I not know about him??!) Especially love #2 of Taylor and his children. And can’t stop thinking about and feeling queasy over the last one. The painting is of the back of a truck, alluding to what happened to James Byrd Jr., a Black man who was chained to a truck by 3 white supremacists in 1998 and dragged to his death. 1998. It was a second ago. I remember the brand of jeans I liked to wear and who I had a crush on and what pop group was in heavy rotation on TRL in 1998. This world is so so grim so much of the time. Thank goodness for art.  #henrytaylor @chinatowntaylor
